{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492485"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:32:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:32:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1079"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1079"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.65,0.02,0.2,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1079"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90493"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1079"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1079"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31032"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90493"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents with a four month history of discomfort in his left leg. This comes on when he has been walking about 400 metres and is relieved with rest. He does not have low back pain. He has a history of hypertension, diabetes and hyperlipidaemia. His current medications include perindopril, atorvastatin and aspirin. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 145/86 mmHg, pulse rate is 78/min and BMI is 28. His abdomen is soft and there are no abnormal findings. The left lower leg is of normal colour, and there are no trophic changes or ulcers. The dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulses are present bilaterally. The hips and the knees have normal ranges of movement. The ankle-brachial index is 1.0 on the right and 0.9 on the left. The value on the left is reduced to 0.6 after exercise.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to advice on smoking cessation, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Toe pressures","Duplex ultrasonography","MRI angiography","CT angiography","Conventional angiography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario suggests a diagnosis of peripheral artery disease and intermittent claudication. It is likely that the toe pressures will be normal and so this measurement will not aid in confirming the diagnosis. To confirm a diagnosis of claudication, in a patient with palpable pulses, an exercise ABI would be the best test. A drop has been determined in this case. Theoretically an ABI less than 0.9 is diagnostic of arterial disease, but a drop in ABI on exercise when the pain comes on will confirm the diagnosis. Anatomical imaging should be done if intervention is considered. In this case, management will start off with lifestyle measures (cessation of smoking and a graded exercise program) before any intervention might be considered. So it would be reasonable to start off with the least invasive and most cost-effective form of imaging - \u003Cstrong\u003Eduplex ultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first imaging investigation in cases of peripheral artery disease should be duplex ultrasonography."],"references":["White C. Intermittent Claudication. N Engl J Med 2007; 356:1241-50.","Barraclough K, Bradbury A. Chronic limb threatening ischaemia. BMJ 2018; 360:j5660."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1079"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74740"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T09:00:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T09:00:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1079"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90493"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo